1 ENGR OSSED SENATE AMENDMENT
TO
2 ENGROSSED HOUSE
BILL NO. 1675 By: Cantrell, Fugate, and
3 Pogemiller of the House
4 and
5 Seifried of the Senate
6
7 An Act relating to emergency management; defining
terms; providing for applicability; directing for
8 assessments and reviews; requiring action plans;
directing for communication and warning systems;
9 providing standards; requiring training and drills;
requiring disclosure; providing for rulemaking;
10 providing enforcement; amending 63 O.S. 2021, Section
681, which relates to school buildings and fallout
11 protection; adding youth camps and recreational
campgrounds; requiring emergency plans be on file
12 with local emergency management director; providing
for codification; providing an effective date; and
13 declaring an emergency.
14
15 AUTHOR: Add the following House Coauthor: Rosecrants
16 AMENDMENT NO. 1. Page 1, strike the title, enacting clause and
entire bill and insert
17
18 “An Act relating to emergency management; defining
terms; providing for applicability; directing for
19 assessments and reviews; requiring action plans;
requiring submission of assessments and plans to
20 regulating authority; providing exception; directing
for communication and warning systems; providing
21 standards; requiring training and drills; requiring
disclosure; providing for rulemaking; providing
22 enforcement; amending 63 O.S. 2021, Section 681,
which relates to school buildings and fallout
23 protection; adding recreational campgrounds;
requiring emergency plans be on file with local
24 emergency management director; updating statutory
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 1

1 language; providing for codification; and providing
an effective date.
2
3 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
4 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24C of Title 63, unless
6 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 As used in this act:
8 1. “Camp facility” means an operator of a facility that hosts
9 or is rented by multiple youth camps;
10 2. “Emergency action plan” or “EAP” means a written, site-
11 specific plan addressing preparedness response, evacuation,
12 sheltering, and communication for severe weather hazards;
13 3. “Hazard exposure zone” means an area identified through
14 federal, state, or local data as subject to one or more severe
15 weather hazards;
16 4. “Outdoor program” means a youth-serving activity conducted
17 primarily outdoors, including wilderness programs, sports camps,
18 adventure camps, or similar operations;
19 5. “Regulating authority” means the emergency management
20 director of the county in which the camp facility, youth camp, or
21 outdoor program is located;
22 6. “Severe weather hazard” means a meteorological or
23 environmental condition that poses a foreseeable risk to life or
24 safety, including but not limited to:
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 2

1 a. flooding or flash flooding,
2 b. high winds or straight-line winds,
3 c. tornadic or rotating wind systems,
4 d. hail,
5 e. lightning,
6 f. extreme heat or cold,
7 g. wildfire or wildfire smoke, and
8 h. any other weather-related condition designated by the
9 regulating authority; and
10 7. “Youth camp” means any program or operation that:
11 a. provides organized recreational, educational, or
12 residential activities,
13 b. serves individuals under eighteen (18) years of age,
14 and
15 c. operates for compensation or as a nonprofit, including
16 day camps, overnight camps, seasonal camps, and
17 specialty camps.
18 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24D of Title 63, unless
20 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 This act applies to all camp facilities, youth camps, and
22 outdoor programs operating within this state except:
23
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 3

1 1. Programs conducted solely on a single-day basis with no
2 oversight component which may be subject to modified requirements,
3 as determined by rule; and
4 2. Programs operated exclusively by a parent or legal guardian
5 for his or her own children.
6 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
7 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24E of Title 63, unless
8 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
9 A. Except as provided for in subsection D of this section, camp
10 facilities, youth camps, and outdoor programs shall conduct a site-
11 specific hazard assessment on or before January 1, 2027,
12 identifying:
13 1. Applicable severe weather hazards;
14 2. Proximity to hazard exposure zones;
15 3. Structural vulnerabilities of buildings and shelters; and
16 4. Feasible evacuation routes and shelter-in-place locations.
17 B. Hazard assessments shall be reviewed and updated:
18 1. At least once every three (3) years; and
19 2. Upon material changes to facilities, terrain, or hazard
20 classifications.
21 C. A copy of the site-specific hazard assessment, including
22 updated assessments, shall be submitted to and placed on file with
23 the regulating authority.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 4

1 D. Any youth camp or outdoor program hosted at a camp facility
2 shall utilize the site-specific hazard assessment of the camp
3 facility.
4 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24F of Title 63, unless
6 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 A. Except as provided for in subsection E of this section, on
8 or before January 1, 2027, camp facilities, youth camps, and outdoor
9 programs shall develop and maintain an emergency action plan
10 addressing, at a minimum:
11 1. Monitoring and detection of severe weather hazards;
12 2. Decision-making authority and chain of command;
13 3. Criteria for evacuation versus shelter-in-place;
14 4. Evacuation routes and secondary alternatives;
15 5. Shelter standards appropriate to the identified hazards;
16 6. Accountability procedures for campers and staff; and
17 7. Post-event communication and reunification procedures.
18 B. The plan shall include separate response protocols for each
19 severe weather hazard reasonably applicable to the site.
20 C. Emergency action plans shall be reviewed and updated:
21 1. At least once every three (3) years; and
22 2. Upon material changes to facilities, terrain, or hazard
23 classifications.
24
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 5

1 D. A copy of the emergency action plan, including updated
2 plans, shall be submitted to and placed on file with the regulating
3 authority.
4 E. Any youth camp or outdoor program hosted at a camp facility
5 shall utilize the emergency action plan of the camp facility.
6 SECTION 5. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
7 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24G of Title 63, unless
8 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
9 Each camp facility, youth camp, and outdoor program shall
10 maintain:
11 1. At least two independent methods of receiving severe weather
12 alerts, including one method that does not rely on cellular service;
13 2. An internal communication system capable of alerting staff
14 and campers promptly; and
15 3. Procedures for notifying parents or guardians during
16 emergencies.
17 SECTION 6. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24H of Title 63, unless
19 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 A. Where severe weather hazards are identified, camp facilities
21 and youth camps shall provide access to shelters that are:
22 1. Appropriately rated for anticipated wind or impact loads;
23 2. Located outside high-risk zones when feasible; and
24 3. Clearly marked and accessible.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 6

1 B. The regulating authority may prohibit or condition the use
2 of:
3 1. Sleeping facilities located in high-risk hazard exposure
4 zones; or
5 2. Temporary structures unable to withstand foreseeable severe
6 weather.
7 SECTION 7. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
8 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24I of Title 63, unless
9 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
10 A. Camp facility, youth camp, and outdoor program staff shall
11 receive annual training on emergency procedures and hazard
12 recognition.
13 B. Youth camps and camp facilities shall conduct periodic
14 drills appropriate to the identified hazards.
15 C. Training records shall be maintained and made available for
16 inspection by the regulating authority.
17 SECTION 8. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
18 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24J of Title 63, unless
19 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
20 Youth camps, camp facilities, and outdoor programs shall
21 disclose in writing:
22 1. The existence of material severe weather hazards affecting
23 the site; and
24 2. The general nature of emergency response procedures.
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 7

1 Acknowledgment of receipt shall be obtained from participants or
2 the parents or legal guardians of participants, if the participant
3 is a minor, prior to participation.
4 SECTION 9. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
5 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 683.24K of Title 63, unless
6 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
7 A. The regulating authority shall adopt rules necessary to
8 implement this act, including:
9 1. Hazard-specific standards;
10 2. Compliance timelines; and
11 3. Variance procedures for site-specific conditions.
12 B. The regulating authority may impose:
13 1. Corrective action plans;
14 2. Civil penalties; or
15 3. The closure of camp facilities, youth camps, and outdoor
16 programs for material noncompliance.
17 SECTION 10. AMENDATORY 63 O.S. 2021, Section 681, is
18 amended to read as follows:
19 Section 681. A. School authorities of the State of Oklahoma
20 this state, its political subdivisions, and its school districts are
21 authorized to plan, design, and construct new school buildings and
22 make additions to existing school buildings that afford protection
23 for the anticipated school body, faculty, and visitors against
24 tornadoes and severe weather. Each school, administration building
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 8

1 and institution of higher learning shall have written plans and
2 procedures in place for protecting students, faculty, administrators
3 and visitors from natural and man-made disasters and emergencies.
4 Plans shall be reviewed and updated annually as appropriate by each
5 school, administration building and institution of higher learning,
6 and placed on file at each school district and each local emergency
7 response organization within the district, which may include police,
8 fire, emergency medical services, sheriff and emergency management
9 of the appropriate jurisdiction. The plans shall be submitted in a
10 format acceptable to the emergency agency no later than November 1
11 of each year. Each school district and institution of higher
12 learning shall make annual reports to the local school board or
13 Board of Regents detailing the status of emergency preparedness and
14 identified safety needs for each school or institution.
15 B. Recreational campgrounds within this state are authorized to
16 plan, design, and maintain facilities and grounds in a manner that
17 affords protection for campers, staff, and visitors against flooding
18 and severe weather hazards. Each recreational campground shall have
19 written emergency action plans and procedures in place for
20 protecting campers, staff, and visitors from natural disasters and
21 severe weather events, including those requiring evacuation.
22 1. Such plans shall, at a minimum, identify natural hazards
23 specific to the location that may necessitate evacuation, outline
24 evacuation routes and procedures, and include methods for issuing
ENGR. S. A. TO ENGR. H. B. NO. 1675 Page 9

1 emer gency alerts and warnings to campers and staff. The plans shall
2 be reviewed and updated annually as appropriate by the operator of
3 the recreational campground.
4 2. A copy of the emergency action plan, including evacuation
5 procedures and warning information, shall be submitted to and placed
6 on file with the local emergency management director of the
7 appropriate jurisdiction in a format acceptable to the emergency
8 management agency. The plans shall be submitted or updated no later
9 than January 1 of each year and upon any significant change to
10 facility operations or hazard conditions.
11 SECTION 11. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.”
12 Passed the Senate the 29th day of April, 2026.
